    <tr><td>Frontend Framework</td><td>React + TypeScript</td><td>18.3</td><td>Component-based UI with type safety</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Build Tool</td><td>Vite</td><td>5.4</td><td>Fast development server and production bundling</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Styling</td><td>Tailwind CSS</td><td>3.4</td><td>Utility-first CSS framework</td></tr>
    <tr><td>UI Components</td><td>shadcn/ui (Radix UI)</td><td>—</td><td>Accessible, composable component primitives</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Charts</td><td>Recharts</td><td>2.15</td><td>React-based data visualization</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ML Framework</td><td>face-api.js (TensorFlow.js)</td><td>0.22</td><td>Browser-based face detection &amp; analysis</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Database</td><td>Firebase Firestore</td><td>10.x</td><td>Real-time NoSQL cloud database</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Routing</td><td>React Router DOM</td><td>6.30</td><td>Client-side page routing</td></tr>
    <tr><td>State Management</td><td>TanStack React Query</td><td>5.x</td><td>Async state management and caching</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Icons</td><td>Lucide React</td><td>0.462</td><td>Consistent icon library</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Notifications</td><td>Sonner</td><td>1.7</td><td>Toast notification system</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Date Utilities</td><td>date-fns</td><td>3.6</td><td>Date formatting and manipulation</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Form Handling</td><td>React Hook Form + Zod</td><td>7.x / 3.x</td><td>Form validation with schema support</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Testing</td><td>Vitest + Testing Library</td><td>3.2</td><td>Unit and component testing</td></tr>
  </table>
  
  <h3>6.1 Why These Technologies?</h3>
  
  <h4>React + TypeScript</h4>
  <p>React provides a component-based architecture ideal for building complex interactive UIs. TypeScript adds compile-time type checking, reducing runtime errors and improving code maintainability — critical for a project involving ML data pipelines.</p>
  
  <h4>face-api.js</h4>
  <p>face-api.js wraps TensorFlow.js with a high-level API specifically designed for face analysis tasks. It provides pre-trained models for detection, landmarks, expressions, age, and gender — eliminating the need for custom model training while delivering good accuracy.</p>
  
  <h4>Firebase Firestore</h4>
  <p>Firestore provides real-time data synchronization, enabling the dashboard to update live as new detections are recorded. Its document-based schema is well-suited to storing individual detection records with flexible fields.</p>
  
  <h4>Vite</h4>
  <p>Vite offers significantly faster development server startup and hot module replacement compared to alternatives like Webpack, improving developer productivity during iterative development.</p>
</div>

<!-- ==================== CHAPTER 7 ==================== -->
<div class="page-break">
  <h2 id="ch7">7. Machine Learning Models</h2>
  
  <p>FaceInsight uses <strong>face-api.js</strong>, a JavaScript API built on top of TensorFlow.js, which provides pre-trained deep learning models for face analysis tasks.</p>
  
  <h3>7.1 Models Used</h3>
  
  <table>
    <tr><th>Model</th><th>Weight File</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Architecture</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Tiny Face Detector</td><td>tiny_face_detector_model</td><td>Face detection &amp; localization</td><td>MobileNetV1-based SSD</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Face Landmark 68</td><td>face_landmark_68_model</td><td>68-point facial landmark detection</td><td>CNN</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Face Expression</td><td>face_expression_model</td><td>7-class emotion classification</td><td>CNN</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Age &amp; Gender</td><td>age_gender_model</td><td>Age estimation &amp; gender classification</td><td>CNN</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Face Recognition</td><td>face_recognition_model</td><td>128-dimensional face descriptor</td><td>ResNet-34</td></tr>
  </table>
  
  <h3>7.2 Model Loading Strategy</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Models are loaded asynchronously when the application mounts</li>
    <li>All 5 models load in parallel using <code>Promise.all()</code> for optimal performance</li>
    <li>A singleton loading promise prevents duplicate network requests</li>
    <li>Models are served as static files from the <code>/public/models/</code> directory</li>
    <li>Total model size: approximately 6MB across sharded weight files</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h3>7.3 Detection Pipeline</h3>
  <p>Each video frame passes through the following sequential pipeline:</p>
  
  <div class="architecture-box">Video Frame
    │
    ▼
TinyFaceDetector
    → Outputs: face bounding box coordinates
    │
    ▼
FaceLandmark68Net
    → Outputs: 68 facial landmark points (eyes, nose, mouth, jaw)
    │
    ▼
FaceExpressionNet
    → Outputs: 7-class emotion probabilities
    │
    ▼
AgeGenderNet
    → Outputs: age estimate (years), gender label + probability
    │
    ▼
Structured FaceDetection Result</div>
  
  <h3>7.4 Emotion Classification Details</h3>
  <p>The Face Expression model outputs a probability distribution across all 7 emotion classes. The dominant emotion is selected as the one with the highest probability score. Both the emotion label and confidence score are stored.</p>
  
  <h3>7.5 Age Group Mapping</h3>
  <p>The AgeGenderNet model outputs a continuous age estimate. This is mapped to discrete age groups using the following logic:</p>
  
  <pre>
function getAgeGroup(age: number): string {
  if (age &lt;= 12) return 'Child';
  if (age &lt;= 19) return 'Teen';
  if (age &lt;= 59) return 'Adult';
  return 'Senior';
}</pre>
</div>

<!-- ==================== CHAPTER 8 ==================== -->
<div class="page-break">
  <h2 id="ch8">8. Data Flow &amp; Privacy Architecture</h2>
  
  <h3>8.1 What IS Stored (Anonymized Data)</h3>
  
  <table>
    <tr><th>Field</th><th>Data Type</th><th>Example Value</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    <tr><td>emotion</td><td>string</td><td>"happy"</td><td>Classified emotion label</td></tr>
    <tr><td>emotion_confidence</td><td>float</td><td>0.92</td><td>Confidence score (0.0–1.0)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>age_group</td><td>string</td><td>"Adult"</td><td>Mapped age category</td></tr>
    <tr><td>age_estimate</td><td>integer</td><td>28</td><td>Predicted age in years</td></tr>
    <tr><td>gender</td><td>string</td><td>"male"</td><td>Predicted gender</td></tr>
    <tr><td>gender_confidence</td><td>float</td><td>0.95</td><td>Gender prediction confidence</td></tr>
    <tr><td>session_id</td><td>UUID</td><td>"a1b2c3d4-..."</td><td>Random session identifier</td></tr>
    <tr><td>timestamp</td><td>ISO string</td><td>"2026-03-12T10:30:00Z"</td><td>Detection time</td></tr>
    <tr><td>created_at</td><td>ISO string</td><td>"2026-03-12T10:30:00Z"</td><td>Record creation time</td></tr>
  </table>
  
  <h3>8.2 What is NEVER Stored</h3>
  <div class="warning-box">
    <ul>
      <li>❌ Face images, video frames, or screenshots</li>
      <li>❌ Facial landmarks or geometric measurements</li>
      <li>❌ Face embeddings, descriptors, or biometric data</li>
      <li>❌ Personal identifiers of any kind</li>
      <li>❌ IP addresses, geolocation, or device fingerprints</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  
  <h3>8.3 Privacy Guarantees</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Client-Side Processing</strong> — All ML inference runs within the browser's JavaScript engine using WebGL acceleration. No video data is transmitted to any external server.</li>
    <li><strong>No Network Transmission of Images</strong> — The webcam MediaStream is consumed locally by the TensorFlow.js runtime; no frame data enters any network request.</li>
    <li><strong>Irreversible Anonymization</strong> — Stored data consists only of categorical labels and scalar confidence values. It is computationally impossible to reconstruct facial images from this data.</li>
    <li><strong>Session Isolation</strong> — Each browser session generates a random UUID via <code>crypto.randomUUID()</code>. Sessions are not linked to user accounts or device identifiers.</li>
    <li><strong>User-Controlled Data</strong> — Users can export all data as JSON and permanently delete all records through the Settings page.</li>
  </ol>
</div>

<!-- ==================== CHAPTER 9 ==================== -->
<div class="page-break">
  <h2 id="ch9">9. Database Schema</h2>
  
  <h3>9.1 Firebase Firestore Collection: <code>face_analytics</code></h3>
  
  <p>All detection results are stored in a single Firestore collection named <code>face_analytics</code>. Each document represents one detected face at a specific point in time.</p>
  
  <pre>
face_analytics/
├── {auto-generated-document-id}
│   ├── emotion: string           // "happy", "sad", "angry", "neutral", etc.
│   ├── emotion_confidence: number // 0.0 – 1.0
│   ├── age_group: string          // "Child", "Teen", "Adult", "Senior"
│   ├── age_estimate: number       // Estimated age (e.g., 25)
│   ├── gender: string             // "male" or "female"
│   ├── gender_confidence: number  // 0.0 – 1.0
│   ├── session_id: string         // Random UUID per browser session
│   ├── timestamp: string          // ISO 8601 formatted timestamp
│   └── created_at: string         // ISO 8601 creation timestamp</pre>
  
  <h3>9.2 Query Patterns</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Query</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Firestore Operations</th></tr>
    <tr><td>All records by time</td><td>Dashboard overview</td><td><code>orderBy('timestamp', 'desc')</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Today's records</td><td>Daily analytics</td><td><code>where('timestamp', '&gt;=', startOfDay)</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Weekly records</td><td>Weekly trends</td><td><code>where('timestamp', '&gt;=', startOfWeek)</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Monthly records</td><td>Monthly insights</td><td><code>where('timestamp', '&gt;=', startOfMonth)</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Real-time updates</td><td>Live dashboard</td><td><code>onSnapshot()</code> listener</td></tr>
  </table>
</div>

<!-- ==================== CHAPTER 10 ==================== -->
<div class="page-break">
  <h2 id="ch10">10. Application Pages</h2>
  
  <h3>10.1 Landing Page (<code>/</code>)</h3>
  <p>The entry point of the application, designed to showcase system capabilities and communicate the privacy-first approach.</p>
  <p><strong>Sections:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Hero Section</strong> — Gradient text headline, privacy badge, and two CTA buttons (Start Analysis, View Dashboard)</li>
    <li><strong>Features Grid</strong> — Six cards highlighting: Real-Time Detection, Emotion Recognition, Demographic Analysis, Analytics Dashboard, Privacy First, Instant Insights</li>
    <li><strong>Privacy Commitment</strong> — Detailed section with shield icon listing all privacy guarantees</li>
    <li><strong>"How It Works"</strong> — Three-step visual flow: Allow Camera → AI Analysis → View Insights</li>
    <li><strong>Call to Action</strong> — Final prompt to begin live analysis</li>
    <li><strong>Footer</strong> — Branding and privacy reminder</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h3>10.2 Live Analysis Page (<code>/analyze</code>)</h3>
  <p>The core analysis page providing real-time face detection with webcam integration.</p>
  <p><strong>Components:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Start/Stop analysis toggle button with loading state</li>
    <li>Live indicator showing detection status</li>
    <li>Real-time counters: faces currently detected and total analyzed</li>
    <li>Video feed with per-face overlays showing bounding boxes, emotion emoji, emotion label with confidence %, age group, and gender</li>
    <li>Privacy badge confirming all processing is local</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h3>10.3 Analytics Dashboard (<code>/dashboard</code>)</h3>
  <p>Comprehensive data visualization page with multiple chart types and filtering.</p>
  <p><strong>Widgets:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Four stat cards: Total Analyzed, Sentiment Score, Positive %, Negative %</li>
    <li>Emotion Pie Chart with color-coded segments</li>
    <li>Sentiment Trend line chart (hourly resolution)</li>
    <li>Age Group bar chart</li>
    <li>Gender × Emotion grouped bar chart</li>
    <li>Sentiment Gauge (0–100 visual gauge)</li>
    <li>Peak Unhappy Times cards</li>
    <li>Time Range Selector: Today / Week / Month / All</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h3>10.4 Settings Page (<code>/settings</code>)</h3>
  <p>Configuration and data management interface.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Camera Settings</strong> — Dropdown to select from available video input devices</li>
    <li><strong>Detection Settings</strong> — Interval slider (100ms–2000ms), database save toggle</li>
    <li><strong>Data Management</strong> — Export as JSON button, Clear All Data button with confirmation</li>
    <li><strong>About</strong> — Version info, ML framework, storage backend, privacy notice</li>
  </ul>
</div>

